column29:
A TEWL measuring device is needed to support an ongoing NIOSH National Occupational Research Agenda (NORA) project – “Investigating Cytokine & Other
Biomarkers in Skin Post Exposure to Drilling Fluids,” wherein changes to skin models will be observed after application of oil and gas drilling fluids to make proper
recommendations regarding the control of exposures. The vapometer from Delfin measures TEWL as well as the evaporation rate. The Delfin
vapometer is the only reasonable available source that can meet all of CBMB’s required salient characteristics for a TEWL measuring device, as follows:
- adaptable instrument that can measure TEWL;
- can measure in both in-vitro (lab) and in-vivo (body) settings;
- equipped with special adapters that allows for testing in 6 well plates, 96 well plates, and Franz cells (9mm), etc.;
- closed chambered to eliminate interferences from surrounding air, especially if
- the instrument is taken into the dynamic environment of an oil and gas site in multiple states (outdoors);
- And portable and battery operated (no cord) in order to take to multiple sites, which would allow for in-vivo studies in outdoor settings.

Nitrile Gloves:
o	4 MIL(Blue), 5 MIL(Blue), and 6 MIL(Black) finger thickness;
o	Meet medical examination grade American Society of Testing Materials (ASTM) D6319;
o	Disposable nitrile exam gloves are powder and latex free;
o	Tested for protection against Fentanyl exposure, and, when intended to be used by the Transportation Security Administration (TSA), pass TSA testing for interference with explosives detection equipment/machines before use; and
o	Gloves are ambidextrous, puncture and chemical resistant.

Nitrile Gloves: 
•	4 MIL, 5 MIL and 6 MIL finger thickness; 
•	Meet medical examination grade American Society of Testing Materials (ASTM) D6319;
•	Disposable nitrile exam gloves are powder and latex free;
•	Tested for protection against Fentanyl exposure; and
•	Gloves are ambidextrous, puncture and chemical resistant.

The PIFSC Fisheries Research and Monitoring Division (FRMD), Life History Program (LHP) provides critical data used in stock assessments, specifically the size and age at maturity as determined by histological analysis of gonad samples and the age and growth as determined by thin mounted otolith slides. A digital whole slide scanner is required by the LHP to scan and archive images of microscope slides. This equipment will allow for increases capacity building and training workshops for life history with jurisdictional partners, allow for remote histology work, allow archiving of high-quality images, enable virtual consultations/collaborations (within and across the center), and provide a necessary backup for existing outdated infrastructure.  Per the market research performed, the Grundium Ocus 40x slide scanner is the only unit that meets all of the government’s salient characteristics.  This unit is a manufactured end product of Finland but is distributed in the U.S. by a small business entity.

Salient Characteristics:
•        Portability- the unit will be shared among multiple PIFSC users and will be used to build life history capacity in the jurisdictions and with agency and 
         university partners. Therefore, it is essential that the unit is easily portable – 20 pounds or less;
•	High resolution - 750x magnification;
•	High speed - < 3min scan time per slide;
•	Automatic focusing during scanning;
•	Open optic design that allows for external light sources to be used for imaging otoliths.

The National Institute on Aging (NIA), Laboratory of Genetics & Genomics (LGG), Functional Epigenomics Unit (FEU) requires an incubator and bioreactor that can grow 3D cultures (spheroids, organoids, cell aggregates and biopsies) that best mimic organ structure in vivo.  The FEU will use the incubator and bioreactor to grow organoids/spheroids of mouse and human tissue over prolonged periods mimicking aging in vitro as well as perform genetic manipulations and drug screens to identify new targets of aging reducing dependence on animal models. Additional salient characteristics are listed below: 

•	Temperature and humidity-controlled chamber; 
•	Ability to rotate at adjustable speeds with very low shear forces; 
•	Allow for the optimal growth of spheroids, and
•	Small footprint due to limited lab space.
